Class PopupPresenter<D extends android.os.Parcelable,R>

  • java.lang.Object
    • mortar.Presenter<Popup<D,R>>
      • mortar.PopupPresenter<D,R>
  • Type Parameters:
    D - the type of info this dialog displays. D must provide value-based implementations of Object.hashCode() and Object.equals(Object) in order for debouncing code in show(D) to work properly. When using multiple PopupPresenters of the same type in the same view, construct them with PopupPresenter(String) to give them a name to distinguish them.

    public abstract class PopupPresenter<D extends android.os.Parcelable,R>

      • dropView

        public void dropView(Popup<D,R> view)
        Description copied from class: Presenter
        Called to surrender control of this view, e.g. when the view is detached. If and only if the given view matches the last passed to Presenter.takeView(V), the reference to the view is cleared.

        Mismatched views are a no-op, not an error. This is to provide protection in the not uncommon case that dropView and takeView are called out of order. For example, an activity's views are typically inflated in android.app.Activity#onCreate, but are only detached some time after onExitScope. It's possible for a view from one activity to be detached well after the window for the next activity has its views inflated—that is, after the next activity's onResume call.

        Overrides:
        dropView in class Presenter<Popup<D extends android.os.Parcelable,R>>

      • onLoad

        public void onLoad(android.os.Bundle savedInstanceState)
        Description copied from class: Presenter
        Like Bundler.onLoad(android.os.Bundle), but called only when Presenter.getView() is not null, and debounced. That is, this method will be called exactly once for a given view instance, at least until that view is dropped. See Presenter.takeView(V) for details.
